                       Sliding Window
ğŸ“Œ What is Sliding Window?
      Sliding Window is a technique used to solve problems involving:
      Subarrays
      Substrings
      Contiguous sequences

Instead of using nested loops (O(nÂ²)), we optimize to O(n) by maintaining a â€œwindowâ€ and sliding it.

there are 2 types
1.fixed size window
2.variable size window


1ï¸âƒ£ Fixed Size Sliding Window

Used when window size k is given.

ğŸ”¹ Example:

Find maximum sum of subarray of size k.

ğŸ§  Idea:

First calculate sum of first k elements

Then slide window:

Add next element

Remove first element of previous window
...............................
input:[2,3,5,8,1,4] k=3
output:16[3,5,8]
logic:
    [2,3,5] sum=10 
         remove 2 and add 8
    [3,5,8] sum=16
        remove 3 and add 1
    [5,8,1] sum=14
        remove 5 and add 4
    [8,1,4] sum=13
        end
   
  .........................
ğŸ’» Java Code:
public class SlidingWindow {
    public static int maxSum(int[] arr, int k) {
        int n = arr.length;
        int windowSum = 0;

        // First window
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            windowSum += arr[i];
        }

        int maxSum = windowSum;

        // Slide window
        for (int i = k; i < n; i++) {
            windowSum += arr[i] - arr[i - k];
            maxSum = Math.max(maxSum, windowSum);
        }

        return maxSum;
    }
}
â± Time Complexity: O(n)
-----------------------------
2ï¸âƒ£ Variable Size Sliding Window

Used when window size is NOT fixed.

Mostly used in:

    Longest substring without repeating characters

    Smallest subarray with sum â‰¥ target

    Longest substring with at most k distinct characters
    ......................
    class Solution {
    public int minSubArrayLen(int target, int[] nums) {

        int i = 0;
        int sum = 0;
        int minLen = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        for (int j = 0; j < nums.length; j++) {
            sum += nums[j];

            while (sum >= target) {
                minLen = Math.min(minLen, j - i + 1);
                sum -= nums[i];
                i++;
            }
        }

        return minLen == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? 0 : minLen;
    }
}
.............................
ğŸ”¹ Example:

Longest substring without repeating characters

ğŸ’» Java Code:
import java.util.*;

public class VariableWindow {
    public static int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        int maxLen = 0;
        HashSet<Character> set = new HashSet<>();

        while (j < s.length()) {
            if (!set.contains(s.charAt(j))) {
                set.add(s.charAt(j));
                maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, j - i + 1);
                j++;
            } else {
                set.remove(s.charAt(i));
                i++;
            }
        }

        return maxLen;
    }
}
â± Time Complexity: O(n)


ğŸ¯ When to Use Sliding Window?

Use it when:

Problem involves contiguous subarray/substring

You see words like:
       longest
       shortest
       maximum
       minimum
       subarray
       substring

âš¡ Sliding Window vs Brute Force
Approach	Time Complexity
Nested loops	O(nÂ²)
Sliding Window	O(n)
